# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: industrial-metabolism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] An **agent-based model** (**ABM**) is a computational model for simulating the actions and interactions of an autonomous agent (both individual or collective entities such as organizations or groups) to understand the behavior of a system and what governs its outcomes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] It combines elements of game theory, complex systems, emergence, computational sociology, multi-agent systems, and evolutionary programming.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Monte Carlo methods are used to understand the stochasticity of these models.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Particularly within ecology, an ABM is also called an **individual-based model** (**IBM**).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] A review of literature on individual-based models, agent-based models, and multiagent systems shows that ABMs are used in many scientific domains including biology, ecology, and social science.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based modeling is related to, but distinct from, the concept of a **multi-agent system** .
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] An agent-based model is a type of microscale model that simulates the simultaneous operations and interactions of multiple agents in an attempt to re-create and predict the appearance of complex phenomena.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The process is one of emergence, which some express as "the whole is greater than the sum of its parts".
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In other words, higher-level system properties emerge from the interactions of lower-level subsystems.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Or, macro-scale state changes emerge from micro-scale agent behaviors.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Or, simple behaviors (meaning rules followed by agents) generate complex behaviors (meaning state changes at the whole system level).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] An individual agent is typically characterized as boundedly rational, presumed to be acting in what it perceives as its their own interests, such as reproduction, economic benefit, or social status, using heuristics or simple decision-making rules.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] An ABM agent may experience "learning", adaptation, and reproduction.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] An agent-based model is usually composed of (1) numerous agents specified at various scales (typically referred to as agent-granularity), (2) decision-making heuristics, (3) learning rules or adaptive processes,(4) an interaction topology, and (5) an environment.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] An ABM is typically implemented as a computer simulation, either as custom software or using an ABM toolkit.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] This software can be then used to test how changes in individual behavior will affect the system's overall behavior.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The idea of agent-based modeling was developed as a relatively simple concept in the late 1940s.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Since it requires computation-intensive procedures, it did not become widespread until the 1990s.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The history of the agent-based model can be traced back to the Von Neumann machine, a theoretical machine capable of reproduction.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The device von Neumann proposed would follow precisely detailed instructions to fashion a copy of itself.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The concept was then built upon by von Neumann's friend Stanislaw Ulam, also a mathematician; Ulam suggested that the machine be built on paper, as a collection of cells on a grid.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The idea intrigued von Neumann, who drew it up — creating the first of the devices later termed cellular automata.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Oliver Selfridge's 1958 Pandemonium - A Paradigm for Learning paper was an important early theorectical contribution in establishing agent orientated architecture, though it used the term metaphorical 'demon' instead of agent.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Carl Hewitt 1973 Actor model contained one of the earliest uses of agents as active entities rather than passive structures.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Another advance was introduced by the mathematician John Conway.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] He constructed the well-known Game of Life.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Unlike von Neumann's machine, the Game of Life operated by simple rules in a virtual world in the form of a 2-dimensional checkerboard.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The Simula programming language, developed in the mid-1960s and widely implemented by the early 1970s, was the first framework for automating step-by-step agent simulations.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] One of the earliest agent-based models in concept was Thomas Schelling's segregation model, which was discussed in his paper "Dynamic Models of Segregation" in 1971.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Though Schelling originally used coins and graph paper rather than computers, his models embodied the basic concept of agent-based models as autonomous agents interacting in a shared environment with an observed aggregate, emergent outcome.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the late 1970s, Paulien Hogeweg and Bruce Hesper began experimenting with individual models of ecology.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] One of their first results was to show that the social structure of bumble-bee colonies emerged as a result of simple rules that govern the behaviour of individual bees.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] They introduced the ToDo principle, referring to the way agents "do what there is to do" at any given time.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the early 1980s, Robert Axelrod hosted a tournament of Prisoner's Dilemma strategies and had them interact in an agent-based manner to determine a winner.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Axelrod would go on to develop many other agent-based models in the field of political science that examine phenomena from ethnocentrism to the dissemination of culture.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] By the late 1980s, Craig Reynolds' work on flocking models contributed to the development of some of the first biological agent-based models that contained social characteristics.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] He tried to model the reality of lively biological agents, known as artificial life, a term coined by Christopher Langton.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] At the same time, during the 1980s, social scientists, mathematicians, operations researchers, and a scattering of people from other disciplines developed Computational and Mathematical Organization Theory (CMOT).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] This field grew as a special interest group of The Institute of Management Sciences (TIMS) and its sister society, the Operations Research Society of America (ORSA).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The 1990s were especially notable for the expansion of ABM within the social sciences, one notable effort was the large-scale ABM, Sugarscape, developed by Joshua M.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Epstein and Robert Axtell to simulate and explore the role of social phenomena such as seasonal migrations, pollution, sexual reproduction, combat, and transmission of disease and even culture.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Other notable 1990s developments included Carnegie Mellon University's Kathleen Carley ABM, to explore the co-evolution of social networks and culture.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The Santa Fe Institute (SFI) was important in encouraging the development of the ABM modeling platform Swarm under the leadership of Christopher Langton.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Research conducted through SFI allowed the expansion of ABM techniques to a number of fields including study of the social and spatial dynamics of small-scale human societies and primates.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] During this 1990s timeframe Nigel Gilbert published the first textbook on Social Simulation: Simulation for the social scientist (1999) and established a journal from the perspective of social sciences: the *Journal of Artificial Societies and Social Simulation* (JASSS).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Other than JASSS, agent-based models of any discipline are within scope of SpringerOpen journal *Complex Adaptive Systems Modeling* (CASM).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Through the mid-1990s, the social sciences thread of ABM began to focus on such issues as designing effective teams, understanding the communication required for organizational effectiveness, and the behavior of social networks.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] CMOT—later renamed Computational Analysis of Social and Organizational Systems (CASOS)—incorporated more and more agent-based modeling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Samuelson (2000) is a good brief overview of the early history, and Samuelson (2005) and Samuelson and Macal (2006) trace the more recent developments.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the late 1990s, the merger of TIMS and ORSA to form INFORMS, and the move by INFORMS from two meetings each year to one, helped to spur the CMOT group to form a separate society, the North American Association for Computational Social and Organizational Sciences (NAACSOS).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Kathleen Carley was a major contributor, especially to models of social networks, obtaining National Science Foundation funding for the annual conference and serving as the first president of NAACSOS.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] She was succeeded by David Sallach of the University of Chicago and Argonne National Laboratory, and then by Michael Prietula of Emory University.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] At about the same time NAACSOS began, the European Social Simulation Association (ESSA) and the Pacific Asian Association for Agent-Based Approach in Social Systems Science (PAAA), counterparts of NAACSOS, were organized.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] As of 2013, these three organizations collaborate internationally.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The First World Congress on Social Simulation was held under their joint sponsorship in Kyoto, Japan, in August 2006.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The Second World Congress was held in the northern Virginia suburbs of Washington, D.C., in July 2008, with George Mason University taking the lead role in local arrangements.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] More recently, Ron Sun developed methods for basing agent-based simulation on models of human cognition, known as cognitive social simulation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Bill McKelvey, Suzanne Lohmann, Dario Nardi, Dwight Read and others at UCLA have also made significant contributions in organizational behavior and decision-making.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Since 1991, UCLA has arranged a conference at Lake Arrowhead, California, that has become another major gathering point for practitioners in this field.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] After the advent of large language models, researchers began applying interacting language models to agent based modeling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In one widely cited paper, agentic language models interacted in a sandbox environment to perform activities like planning birthday parties and holding elections.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Most computational modeling research describes systems in equilibrium or as moving between equilibria.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based modeling, however, using simple rules, can result in different sorts of complex and interesting behavior.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The three ideas central to agent-based models are agents as objects, emergence, and complexity.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models consist of dynamically interacting rule-based agents.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The systems within which they interact can create real-world-like complexity.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Typically agents are situated in space and time and reside in networks or in lattice-like neighborhoods.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The location of the agents and their responsive behavior are encoded in algorithmic form in computer programs.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In some cases, though not always, the agents may be considered as intelligent and purposeful.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In ecological ABM (often referred to as "individual-based models" in ecology), agents may, for example, be trees in a forest, and would not be considered intelligent, although they may be "purposeful" in the sense of optimizing access to a resource (such as water).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The modeling process is best described as inductive.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The modeler makes those assumptions thought most relevant to the situation at hand and then watches phenomena emerge from the agents' interactions.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Sometimes that result is an equilibrium.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Sometimes, however, it is an unintelligible mangle.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In some ways, agent-based models complement traditional analytic methods.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Where analytic methods enable humans to characterize the equilibria of a system, agent-based models allow the possibility of generating those equilibria.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] This generative contribution may be the most mainstream of the potential benefits of agent-based modeling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models can explain the emergence of higher-order patterns—network structures of terrorist organizations and the Internet, power-law distributions in the sizes of traffic jams, wars, and stock-market crashes, and social segregation that persists despite populations of tolerant people.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models also can be used to identify lever points, defined as moments in time in which interventions have extreme consequences, and to distinguish among types of path dependency.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Rather than focusing on stable states, many models consider a system's robustness—the ways that complex systems adapt to internal and external pressures so as to maintain their functionalities.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The task of harnessing that complexity requires consideration of the agents themselves—their diversity, connectedness, and level of interactions.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Exploratory Agent-based Modeling Level for developing agent-based models for assessing the feasibility of further research.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] This can e.g. be useful for developing proof-of-concept models such as for funding applications without requiring an extensive learning curve for the researchers.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Descriptive Agent-based Modeling (DREAM) for developing descriptions of agent-based models by means of using templates and complex network-based models.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Building DREAM models allows model comparison across scientific disciplines.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Validated agent-based modeling using Virtual Overlay Multiagent system (VOMAS) for the development of verified and validated models in a formal manner.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Other methods of describing agent-based models include code templates and text-based methods such as the ODD (Overview, Design concepts, and Design Details) protocol.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The role of the environment where agents live, both macro and micro, is also becoming an important factor in agent-based modelling and simulation work.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Simple environment affords simple agents, but complex environments generate diversity of behavior.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] One strength of agent-based modelling is its ability to mediate information flow between scales.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] When additional details about an agent are needed, a researcher can integrate it with models describing the extra details.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] When one is interested in the emergent behaviours demonstrated by the agent population, they can combine the agent-based model with a continuum model describing population dynamics.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the resulting modular model, signal transduction and gene regulation are described by a logical model, metabolism by constraint-based models, cell population dynamics are described by an agent-based model, and systemic cytokine concentrations by ordinary differential equations.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In this multi-scale model, the agent-based model occupies the central place and orchestrates every stream of information flow between scales.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have also been used for developing decision support systems such as for breast cancer.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models are increasingly being used to model pharmacological systems in early stage and pre-clinical research to aid in drug development and gain insights into biological systems that would not be possible *a priori*.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Military applications have also been evaluated.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Moreover, agent-based models have been recently employed to study molecular-level biological systems.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have also been written to describe ecological processes at work in ancient systems, such as those in dinosaur environments and more recent ancient systems as well.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models now complement traditional compartmental models, the usual type of epidemiological models.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs have been shown to be superior to compartmental models in regard to the accuracy of predictions.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Recently, ABMs such as CovidSim by epidemiologist Neil Ferguson, have been used to inform public health (nonpharmaceutical) interventions against the spread of SARS-CoV-2.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Epidemiological ABMs have been criticized for simplifying and unrealistic assumptions.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Still, they can be useful in informing decisions regarding mitigation and suppression measures in cases when ABMs are accurately calibrated.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The ABMs for such simulations are mostly based on synthetic populations, since the data of the actual population is not always available.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based models have been used since the mid-1990s to solve a variety of business and technology problems.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Examples of applications include marketing, organizational behaviour and cognition, team working, supply chain optimization and logistics, modeling of consumer behavior, including word of mouth, social network effects, distributed computing, workforce management, and portfolio management.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] They have also been used to analyze traffic congestion.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Recently, agent based modelling and simulation has been applied to various domains such as studying the impact of publication venues by researchers in the computer science domain (journals versus conferences).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In addition, ABMs have been used to simulate information delivery in ambient assisted environments.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] A November 2016 article in arXiv analyzed an agent based simulation of posts spread in Facebook.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the domain of peer-to-peer, ad hoc and other self-organizing and complex networks, the usefulness of agent based modeling and simulation has been shown.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The use of a computer science-based formal specification framework coupled with wireless sensor networks and an agent-based simulation has recently been demonstrated.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent based evolutionary search or algorithm is a new research topic for solving complex optimization problems.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] In the realm of team science, agent-based modeling has been utilized to assess the effects of team members' characteristics and biases on team performance across various settings.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] By simulating interactions between agents—each representing individual team members with distinct traits and biases—this modeling approach enables researchers to explore how these factors collectively influence the dynamics and outcomes of team performance.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Consequently, agent-based modeling provides a nuanced understanding of team science, facilitating a deeper exploration of the subtleties and variabilities inherent in team-based collaborations.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Prior to, and during the 2008 financial crisis, interest has grown in ABMs as possible tools for economic analysis.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs do not assume the economy can achieve equilibrium and "representative agents" are replaced by agents with diverse, dynamic, and interdependent behavior including herding.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs take a "bottom-up" approach and can generate extremely complex and volatile simulated economies.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs can represent unstable systems with crashes and booms that develop out of non-linear (disproportionate) responses to proportionally small changes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] A July 2010 article in *The Economist* looked at ABMs as alternatives to DSGE models.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The journal *Nature* also encouraged agent-based modeling with an editorial that suggested ABMs can do a better job of representing financial markets and other economic complexities than standard models along with an essay by J.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Doyne Farmer and Duncan Foley that argued ABMs could fulfill both the desires of Keynes to represent a complex economy and of Robert Lucas to construct models based on microfoundations.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Farmer and Foley pointed to progress that has been made using ABMs to model parts of an economy, but argued for the creation of a very large model that incorporates low level models.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] By modeling a complex system of analysts based on three distinct behavioral profiles – imitating, anti-imitating, and indifferent – financial markets were simulated to high accuracy.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Results showed a correlation between network morphology and the stock market index.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] However, the ABM approach has been criticized for its lack of robustness between models, where similar models can yield very different results.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs have been deployed in architecture and urban planning to evaluate design and to simulate pedestrian flow in the urban environment and the examination of public policy applications to land-use.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] There is also a growing field of socio-economic analysis of infrastructure investment impact using ABM's ability to discern systemic impacts upon a socio-economic network.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Heterogeneity and dynamics can be easily built in ABM models to address wealth inequality and social mobility.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs have also been proposed as applied educational tools for diplomats in the field of international relations and for domestic and international policymakers to enhance their evaluation of public policy.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] ABMs have also been applied in water resources planning and management, particularly for exploring, simulating, and predicting the performance of infrastructure design and policy decisions, and in assessing the value of cooperation and information exchange in large water resources systems.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agents for Systems are divided in two subcategories.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-supported systems deal with the use of agents as a support facility to enable computer assistance in problem solving or enhancing cognitive capabilities.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Agent-based systems focus on the use of agents for the generation of model behavior in a system evaluation (system studies and analyses).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Hallerbach et al. discussed the application of agent-based approaches for the development and validation of automated driving systems via a digital twin of the vehicle-under-test and microscopic traffic simulation based on independent agents.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Waymo has created a multi-agent simulation environment Carcraft to test algorithms for self-driving cars.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] It simulates traffic interactions between human drivers, pedestrians and automated vehicles.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] People's behavior is imitated by artificial agents based on data of real human behavior.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The basic idea of using agent-based modeling to understand self-driving cars was discussed as early as 2003.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Many ABM frameworks are designed for serial von-Neumann computer architectures, limiting the speed and scalability of implemented models.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Since emergent behavior in large-scale ABMs is dependent of population size, scalability restrictions may hinder model validation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Such limitations have mainly been addressed using distributed computing, with frameworks such as Repast HPC specifically dedicated to these types of implementations.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] While such approaches map well to cluster and supercomputer architectures, issues related to communication and synchronization, as well as deployment complexity, remain potential obstacles for their widespread adoption.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] A recent development is the use of data-parallel algorithms on Graphics Processing Units GPUs for ABM simulation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] The extreme memory bandwidth combined with the sheer number crunching power of multi-processor GPUs has enabled simulation of millions of agents at tens of frames per second.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Since Agent-Based Modeling is more of a modeling framework than a particular piece of software or platform, it has often been used in conjunction with other modeling forms.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] For instance, agent-based models have also been combined with Geographic Information Systems (GIS).
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] This provides a useful combination where the ABM serves as a process model and the GIS system can provide a model of pattern.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Similarly, Social Network Analysis (SNA) tools and agent-based models are sometimes integrated, where the ABM is used to simulate the dynamics on the network while the SNA tool models and analyzes the network of interactions.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Tools like GAMA provide a natural way to integrate system dynamics and GIS with ABM.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Verification and validation (V&V) of simulation models is extremely important.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Verification involves making sure the implemented model matches the conceptual model, whereas validation ensures that the implemented model has some relationship to the real-world.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Face validation, sensitivity analysis, calibration, and statistical validation are different aspects of validation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] A discrete-event simulation framework approach for the validation of agent-based systems has been proposed.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] A comprehensive resource on empirical validation of agent-based models can be found here.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] As an example of V&V technique, consider VOMAS (virtual overlay multi-agent system), a software engineering based approach, where a virtual overlay multi-agent system is developed alongside the agent-based model.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Muazi et al. also provide an example of using VOMAS for verification and validation of a forest fire simulation model.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Another software engineering method, i.e.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] Test-Driven Development has been adapted to for agent-based model validation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/agent-based-model] This approach has another advantage that allows an automatic validation using unit test tools.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Recycling scrap aluminium requires only 5% of the energy used to make new aluminium from the raw ore.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] In 2022, the United States produced 3.86 metric tons of secondary aluminium for every metric ton of primary aluminium produced.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Over the same time period, secondary aluminium accounted for 34% of the total new supply of aluminium including imports.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Used beverage containers are the largest component of processed aluminium scrap, and most of it is manufactured back into aluminium cans.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The first step in aluminium recycling is the collection and sorting of aluminium scrap from various sources.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Scrap aluminium comes primarily from either manufacturing scrap or end-of-life aluminium products such as vehicles, building materials, and consumer products.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Manufacturing scrap includes shreds, shavings, cuttings, and other leftover aluminium from manufacturing processes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Post-consumer scrap consists of obsolete or discarded aluminium products.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium cans, in particular, are a major source of recyclable aluminium scrap.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Once collected, aluminium scrap is sorted based on alloy type, grade, impurity levels, and other factors.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Sorting may be done manually or using technologies like eddy current separators, air classifiers, and density separators.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The scrap is sorted into categories like wrought alloy scrap, casting alloy scrap, used beverage cans, automobile scrap, and mixed scrap.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Proper sorting is essential for producing high-quality recycled aluminium.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] After sorting, the scrap may undergo pre-treatment processes to prepare it for melting.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] These can include baling, shredding, crushing, granulating, decoating, and demagnetizing.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Shredding and crushing reduce the particle size of the scrap and liberate it from other materials, while granulating produces fine particles ideal for melting.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Thermal decoating removes coatings like paint and plastic from aluminium surfaces.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Demagnetizing removes iron particles clinging to the aluminium scrap.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Pre-treatment improves the density of the scrap charge and removes contaminants, resulting in faster melting, cleaner metal, reduced dross formation, and lower energy consumption.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Once pre-treated, the aluminium scrap undergoes melting and liquid metal treatment to produce refined aluminium alloy suitable for casting or reprocessing.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Different furnace types are used based on the type of scrap, desired metal quality, and economics.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Smaller scrap is typically processed in rotary or reverberatory gas-fired furnaces, while large individual pieces of scrap can be charged directly into reverb furnaces through side wells.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Electric induction furnaces are also used.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] As the scrap melts, fluxes are added to bind and absorb impurities which are scraped off the top as dross.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Chlorine gas may also be injected to remove impurities through flotation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The melt can then undergo refining processes like flux injection to further reduce hydrogen and impurities.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Degassing removes dissolved hydrogen while chemical filtration removes solid impurities and inclusions.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The final result is molten aluminium alloy ready for casting.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The molten recycled aluminium is cast into solid forms such as ingots, sows, or directly into sheets or extrusion billets.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Direct-chill casting is commonly used to solidify the liquid aluminium into large cylindrical billets for extrusion or rolling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The direct chill method sprays water onto the hot metal as it exits the mold, quickly chilling it into a solid billet form.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] For ingots, book molds are often used, producing slabbed ingots suitable for remelting or rolling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Continuous casting directly shapes the aluminium into rolling slabs without an intermediate ingot casting step.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Twin-belt or twin-roll strip casting produces alloy strips 6-7mm thick directly from the melt for subsequent rolling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The casting method depends on the subsequent processing and use of the recycled aluminium alloy.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Although aluminium in its pure form has been produced as early as 1825, secondary aluminium production, or recycling, rose in volume with the introduction of industrially viable primary aluminium processes, namely the combination of the Bayer and Hall-Héroult processes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The Hall-Héroult process for aluminium production from alumina was invented in 1886 by Charles Hall and Paul Héroult.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Carl Josef Bayer created a multi-step process to convert raw bauxite into alumina in 1888.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] As aluminium production rose with the use of these two processes, aluminium recycling grew too.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] In 1904, the first two aluminium can recycling plants were built in the United States; one recycling plant was built in Chicago, Illinois and the other was built in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium recycling increased most significantly in volume when metal resources were strained during WWI, as the U.S. government campaigned for civilians to donate old products such as aluminium pots, pans, boats, vehicles, and toys to recycle for the construction of aluminium airframes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium is an infinitely recyclable material, and it takes up to 95 percent less energy to recycle it than to produce primary aluminium, which also limits emissions, including greenhouse gases.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Today, about 75 percent of all aluminium produced in history, nearly a billion tons, is still in use.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The recycling of aluminium generally produces significant cost savings over the production of new aluminium, even when the cost of collection, separation and recycling are taken into account.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Over the long term, even larger national savings are made when the reduction in the capital costs associated with landfills, mines, and international shipping of raw aluminium are considered.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Recycling aluminium uses about 5% of the energy required to create aluminium from bauxite; the amount of energy required to convert aluminium oxide into aluminium can be vividly seen when the process is reversed during the combustion of thermite or ammonium perchlorate composite propellant.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium die extrusion is a specific way of getting reusable material from aluminium scraps but does not require a large energy output of a melting process.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] In 2003, half of the products manufactured with aluminium were sourced from recycled aluminium material.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The benefit with respect to emissions of carbon dioxide depends in part on the type of energy used.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Electrolysis can be done using electricity from non-fossil-fuel sources, such as nuclear, geothermal, hydroelectric, or solar.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium production is attracted to sources of cheap electricity.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Canada, Brazil, Norway, and Venezuela have 61 to 99% hydroelectric power and are major aluminium producers.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] However the anodes widely used in the Hall–Héroult process are made of carbon and are consumed during aluminium production, generating large quantities of carbon dioxide, regardless of electricity source.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Efforts are underway to eliminate the need for carbon anodes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The use of recycled aluminium also decreases the need for mining and refining bauxite.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The vast amount of aluminium used means that even small percentage losses are large expenses, so the flow of material is well monitored and accounted for financial reasons.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Efficient production and recycling benefits the environment as well.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Because many countries continue to rely on coal-generated electricity for aluminium production, the aluminium industry contributes to 2% of global greenhouse gas emissions, around 1.1 billion tons of carbon dioxide.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Many countries now seek to decarbonize aluminium not only as it is the second most used metal in the world, but also because it would heavily address the total greenhouse gas emissions in an effort to slow climate change.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] As one of the most recyclable –and recycled– materials in use today, aluminium can be virtually infinitely recycled.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Since recycled aluminium takes 5% of the energy used to make new aluminium, around 75% of aluminium manufactured continues to be in use today.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] According to the Aluminium Association, in industrial markets such as automotive and building, aluminium is recycled at rates of up to 90%.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Since 1991, greenhouse gas emissions from aluminium cans have dropped about 40%, similar to energy demand levels.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] This can be attributed to a reduction in the carbon intensity of primary aluminium production, improving the efficacy of manufacturing operations, and lighter cans.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] While primary aluminium only accounts for 26.6% of the can, it makes up the major source of the can's carbon footprint.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] For example, as of 2020, 86% of China's aluminium production relies mostly on coal-generated electricity.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] On the other hand, Canada sources roughly 90% of its primary aluminium production using hydroelectric power, considering it to be the most sustainable in the world.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium and its applications are wide and numerous–from defense construction and electrical transmission to playing a key role in emission-reducing goods (electric vehicles and solar panels).
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] As such, countries have begun to decarbonize aluminium to combat global climate change.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Aluminium recycling has several economic benefits when done properly.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] In fact, the Environmental Protection Agency considers recycling a "critical" part of the United States economy, contributing to tax revenue, wages, and job creation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] By facilitating scrap handling and improving its efficiency – from "end of life" scrap to repurposing scrap throughout the production stage ("in-house" scrap) – aluminium recycling helps in achieving the goals of a circular economy.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] This type of economy focuses on minimizing the extraction of natural resources, leading to a reduction of consumer and industrial waste.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] A few examples of countries that have adopted the shift to a circular economy include the European Union, Finland, France, Slovenia, Italy, Germany, and the Netherlands.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] A study conducted in the United States found several ways that aluminium recycling has proven to have economic benefits.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The process increased the wages of waste management and the recycling industry from $2.1 billion to $5 billion, created more than 100,000 jobs in the United States economy, and produced $1.6 billion in material sales.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] It also saves enough energy to power 1.5 million homes per year, and keeps more than 1 million tons of waste out of landfills every year.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] According to 2020 data from the International Aluminium Institute, the global recycling efficiency rate is 76%.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Around 75% of the almost 1.5 billion tonnes of aluminium ever produced is still in productive use today.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Brazil recycles 98.2% of its aluminium can production, equivalent to 14.7 billion beverage cans per year, ranking first in the world, more than Japan's 82.5% recovery rate.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Brazil has topped the aluminium can recycling charts eight years in a row.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Aside from recycled aluminium beverage cans, the majority of recycled aluminium comes in a mixture of different alloys.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Those alloys generally have high percentages of silicon (Si) and require additional refinement during the shredding, sorting, and refining process to reduce impurities.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Due to the levels of impurities found after refinement, the applications of recycled aluminium alloys are limited to castings and extrusions.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The aerospace industry often restrict impurity levels of Si and Fe in alloys to a 0.40% maximum.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Controlling the appearance of these elements is increasingly difficult the more often the metal has been recycled and require higher cost operations for the alloys to meet performance requirements.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] White dross, a residue from primary aluminium production and secondary recycling operations, usually classified as waste, still contains useful quantities of aluminium which can be extracted industrially.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] The process produces aluminium billets, together with a highly complex waste material.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] It reacts with water, releasing a mixture of gases (including, among others, hydrogen, acetylene, and ammonia) which spontaneously ignites on contact with air; contact with damp air results in the release of copious quantities of ammonia gas.
[src:industrial-metabolism/aluminium-recycling] Despite these difficulties, however, the waste has found use as a filler in asphalt and concrete.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] In layman's terms, anthropogenic metabolism indicates the human impact on the world by the modern industrialized world.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Much of these impacts include waste management, ecological footprints, water footprints, and flow analysis (i.e., the rate at which each human depleted the energy around them).
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Most anthropogenic metabolism happens in developed countries.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] A water footprint is the amount of water that each person uses in their daily lives.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Most of the world's water is salt water which cannot be used in human food or water supplies.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Therefore, the freshwater sources that were once plentiful are now being diminished due to anthropogenic metabolism of the growing population.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] The water footprint encompasses how much fresh water is needed for each consumer's needs.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Allan, "there is a huge impact of water use on stores of surface and groundwater and on flows to which water is returned after use.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] These impacts are shown to be particularly high for manufacturing industries.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] For example, that there are less than 10 economies worldwide that have a significant water surplus, but that these economies have successfully met, or have the potential to meet, the water deficits of the other 190 economies.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Consumers enjoy the delusion of food and water security provided by virtual water trade.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] In addition, the ecological footprint is a more economical and land-focused way of looking at human impact.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Developed countries tend to have higher ecological footprints, which do not strictly correspond to a country's total population.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] According to research by Dias de Oliveira, Vaughan and Rykiel, "The Ecological Footprint...is an accounting tool based on two fundamental concepts, sustainability and carrying capacity.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] One of the major cycles that humans can contribute to that cause a major impact on climate change is the nitrogen cycle.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] This comes from nitrogen fertilizers that humans use.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Gruber and Galloway have researched, "The massive acceleration of the nitrogen cycle caused by the production and industrial use of artificial nitrogen fertilizers worldwide has led to a range of environmental problems.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] The carbon cycle is another major contributor to climate change primarily from anthropogenic metabolism.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] A couple examples of how humans contribute to the carbon in the atmosphere is by burning fossil fuels and deforestation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Impact of climate change extend beyond humans.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] There is a forecast for extinctions of species because of their habitats being affected.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] There are major impacts on the marine systems as a result of anthropogenic metabolism, according to Blaustein, the dramatic findings indicate that "every square kilometer [is] affected by some anthropogenic driver of ecological change".
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] The negative effects of anthropogenic metabolism are seen through the water footprint, ecological footprint, carbon cycle, and the nitrogen cycle.
[src:industrial-metabolism/anthropogenic-metabolism] Studies on the marine ecosystem that show major impacts by humans and developed countries which include more industries, thus more anthropogenic metabolism.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] The strength of appliance recycling legislation and the percentage of appliances recycled varies around the world.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] A key part of appliance recycling is the manual dismantling of each product, removing hazardous components, and recovering reusable materials and parts.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Procedures vary and depend on the appliance type.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] The amount of hazardous components able to be removed also depends on the type of appliance.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Low removal rates of hazardous components reduce the recyclability of valuable materials.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Each type of appliance has its own set of characteristics and components.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] This makes characterization of appliances essential to sorting and separating parts.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Research on appliance dismantling has become an active area, intending to help recycling reach maximum efficiency.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] There is a certain process used to recover materials from appliances.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Parts are generally removed in order from largest to smallest.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Metals are extracted first and then plastics.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Materials are sorted by either size, shape, or density.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Sizing is a good means of sorting to quicken future processing.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] It also classifies fractions that show composition.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Materials report to larger or finer fractions based on original dimension, toughness, or brittleness.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Shape classification contributes to the dynamics of the material.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Classification by density is important when it comes to determining the use of a material.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Batteries and copper are sorted out first for quality control purposes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Next, iron and steel (ferrous metals) are extracted using electromagnets.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] They are collected and made ready for sale.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Then metals are separated from non-metals using eddy currents created by rapidly alternating magnetic fields, which induce metals to jump away from non-metals.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Then water separation is used to sort plastics and glass from circuit boards and copper wires.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Circuit boards and copper content is then sold.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Plastics and glass are further compacted for reuse.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Although appliance recycling is relatively new, several countries have enacted laws and regulations regarding electric waste.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] The first countries to establish home appliance recycling included Japan, Switzerland, Sweden, the Netherlands, and Germany.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] In 2003 the Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Directive (WEEE) became European Law.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] It sets collection, recycling and recovery targets for all types of electrical goods.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] By the 1950s and 60s Japan had already become a major producer of electric appliances.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] The first initiatives to recycle were launched in the 70s.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Due to costs, disassembly was hardly achievable.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] The Home Appliance Recycling Law was enacted in 1998 and came into force in 2001, and recycling of waste electrics became a legal requirement under the Specific Household Appliance Recycling Law and the Law for Promotion of Effective Utilisation Resources.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Appliance manufacturers are now required to finance the recycling of their products.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] The Association for Electric Home Appliances is a trade group that is responsible for orphaned products.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] China produces a significant proportion of the world's appliances, and imports a large quantity of waste appliances.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] There has not been much progress in appliance recycling efficiency.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] China's undeveloped dismantling and processing has led to elevated levels of toxic chemicals in and near waste appliance sites.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] The United States is the largest waste appliance producer in the world.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] There is no federal law requiring appliance recycling; legislation varies between states.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] On a state level, many mandatory electronic recovery programs have been implemented.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] There are several commercial appliance recyclers.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] In 2003, the California Electronic Waste Recycling Act was signed.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] It established a new program for consumers to return, recycle, and ensure the safe and environmentally sound disposal of video display devices, such as televisions and computer monitors, that are hazardous wastes when discarded.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] In 2005, consumers began paying a 6-10 dollar fee when buying an electronic device.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] These fees are used to pay e-waste collectors and recyclers to cover their cost of managing e-waste.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] The EWRA classifies e-waste by dividing the products into two categories: electronic devices and covered electronic devices.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Only covered electronic devices (CEDs) are included in the EWRA, however all electronic devices needed recycling measures to be taken.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] The CEDs include televisions and computers that have LCD displays or contain cathode-ray tubes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] There are several commercial appliance recyclers in Australia.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Some organisations that remove waste appliances and offer government-sponsored rebates.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Some retailers including Appliances Online remove and recycle customers' old appliances.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] In New Zealand there is a push to keep old appliances and e-waste out of landfills, however there is little legislation to preventing this.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] As in Australia there are companies including the manufacturer Fisher and Paykel that remove waste appliances and recycle them.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Extended producer responsibility (EPR) is defined as an environmental protection strategy that makes the manufacturer of the appliance responsible for its entire life cycle and especially for the “take-back”, recycling and final disposal of the product.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Essentially, manufacturers must now finance product treatment and recycling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Countries in which EPR has long been established, demonstrate that the combination of government legislation and sound company practices can produce a higher take-back and recycling rate.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] An example of this is the Sony Corporation in Japan, achieving a 53% recycling rate.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Other ways countries approach the issue of waste appliances is either by offering recycling facilities or banning importation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Almost all countries, at least offer facilities that aid in appliance recycling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/appliance-recycling] Many implement extended producer responsibility, in addition to recycling facilities.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The American English terms *asphalt* (or *asphaltic*) *concrete*, *bituminous asphalt concrete*, and *bituminous mixture* are typically used only in engineering and construction documents, which define concrete as any composite material composed of mineral aggregate adhered with a binder.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The abbreviation, *AC*, is sometimes used for *asphalt concrete* but can also denote *asphalt content* or *asphalt cement*, referring to the liquid asphalt portion of the composite material.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The Procession Street of Babylonian King Nabopolassar, c.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] 625 BC, leading north from his palace through the city's wall, was described as being constructed from burnt brick and asphalt.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Natural asphalt covered and bonded cobblestones were used from 1824 in France as a means to construct roads, as were moulded asphalt cobbles or blocks, formed from rammed natural rock asphalt.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In 1829 natural Seyssel asphalt mixed with 7% aggregate, to create an asphat-mastic surface, was used for a footpath at Pont Morand, Lyon, France, the technique spreading to Paris in 1835, London, England, in 1836, and Philadelphia, United States, in 1838.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Claridge obtained a similar English patent (GB patent 1837 #7849), substituting Seyssel asphalt as the binder, having seen it employed in France and Belgium; he would subsequently form the Claridge's Patent Asphalte Company, in 1838.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] A 2-mile (3.2 km) stretch of a gravel constructed road, running out of Nottingham, was experimentally covered in natural asphalt in 1840.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This experiment was repeated in 1845 in Huntingdon High Street.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] A macadam road surfaced with asphalt was constructed in 1852, between Paris and Perpignan, France, using Swiss Val de Travers rock asphalt (natural asphalt-covered limestone aggregate).
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In 1869, Threadneedle Street, in London, was resurfaced with Swiss Val de Travers rock asphalt.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] He filed a UK patent, in 1902, for his improvement.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Hooley founding a UK company to market the technology, where the term *tar macadam*, shortened to *tarmac*, was coined, after the name of his company *Tar Macadam (Purnell Hooley's Patent) Syndicate Limited*, derived from the combination of tar and macadam gravel composite mixtures.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] and drying the aggregate to remove moisture from it prior to mixing.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Paving and compaction must be performed while the asphalt is sufficiently hot.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In many locales paving is restricted to summer months because in winter the base will cool the asphalt too quickly before it can be packed to the required density.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] It is also used as an environmental liner for landfills, reservoirs, and fish hatchery ponds.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] or sometimes water to the asphalt binder prior to mixing.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This improves working conditions, and lowers laying-temperature, which leads to more rapid availability of the surface for use, which is important for construction sites with critical time schedules.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The usage of these additives in hot-mixed asphalt (above) may afford easier compaction and allow cold-weather paving or longer hauls.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] A survey of US asphalt producers found that nearly 25% of asphalt produced in 2012 was warm mix, a 416% increase since 2009.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Cleaner road pavements can be potentially developed by combining WMA and material recycling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Warm Mix Asphalt (WMA) technology has environmental, production, and economic benefits.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] While in its emulsified state, the bitumen is less viscous and the mixture is easy to work and compact.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The emulsion will break after enough water evaporates and the cold mix will, ideally, take on the properties of an HMA pavement.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Cold mix is commonly used as a patching material and on lesser-trafficked service roads.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] While in its dissolved state, the bitumen is less viscous and the mix is easy to work and compact.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] After the mix is laid down the lighter fraction evaporates.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] in the lighter fraction, cut-back asphalt has been largely replaced by asphalt emulsion.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This is produced by heating hard grade blown bitumen (i.e., partly oxidised) in a green cooker (mixer) until it has become a viscous liquid after which the aggregate mix is then added.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The bitumen aggregate mixture is cooked (matured) for around 6–8 hours and once it is ready, the mastic asphalt mixer is transported to the work site where experienced layers empty the mixer and either machine or hand lay the mastic asphalt contents on to the road.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] while offering as very high fatigue strengths.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] High-modulus asphalt layers are used both in reinforcement operations and in the construction of new reinforcements for medium and heavy traffic.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In base layers, they tend to exhibit a greater capacity of absorbing tensions and, in general, better fatigue resistance.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In addition to the asphalt and aggregate, additives, such as polymers, and antistripping agents may be added to improve the properties of the final product.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Areas paved with asphalt concrete—especially airport aprons—have been called "the tarmac" at times, despite not being constructed using the tarmacadam process.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] A variety of specialty asphalt concrete mixtures have been developed to meet specific needs, such as stone-matrix asphalt, which is designed to ensure a strong wearing surface, or porous asphalt pavements, which are permeable and allow water to drain through the pavement for controlling storm water.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Different types of asphalt concrete have different performance characteristics in roads in terms of surface durability, tire wear, braking efficiency and roadway noise.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In principle, the determination of appropriate asphalt performance characteristics must take into account the volume of traffic in each vehicle category, and the performance requirements of the friction course.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In general, the viscosity of asphalt allows it to conveniently form a convex surface, and a central apex to streets and roads to drain water to the edges.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This is not, however, in itself an advantage over concrete, which has various grades of viscosity and can be formed into a convex road surface.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Rather, it is the economy of asphalt concrete that renders it more frequently used.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Concrete is found on interstate highways where maintenance is highly crucial.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Asphalt concrete generates less roadway noise than a Portland cement concrete surface, and is typically less noisy than chip seal surfaces.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Because tire noise is generated through the conversion of kinetic energy to sound waves, more noise is produced as the speed of a vehicle increases.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The notion that highway design might take into account acoustical engineering considerations, including the selection of the type of surface paving, arose in the early 1970s.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] With regard to structural performance, the asphalt behaviour depends on a variety of factors including the material, loading and environmental condition.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Furthermore, the performance of pavement varies over time.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Therefore, the long-term behaviour of asphalt pavement is different from its short-term performance.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The LTPP is a research program by the FHWA, which is specifically focusing on long-term pavement behaviour.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Asphalt deterioration can include crocodile cracking, potholes, upheaval, raveling, bleeding, rutting, shoving, stripping, and grade depressions.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In cold climates, frost heaves can crack asphalt even in one winter.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Filling the cracks with bitumen is a temporary fix, but only proper compaction and drainage can slow this process.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Factors that cause asphalt concrete to deteriorate over time mostly fall into one of three categories: construction quality, environmental considerations, and traffic loads.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Often, damage results from combinations of factors in all three categories.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Construction quality is critical to pavement performance.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This includes the construction of utility trenches and appurtenances that are placed in the pavement after construction.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Lack of compaction in the surface of the asphalt, especially on the longitudinal joint, can reduce the life of a pavement by 30 to 40%.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Service trenches in pavements after construction have been said to reduce the life of the pavement by 50%, mainly due to the lack of compaction in the trench, and because of water intrusion through improperly sealed joints.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Environmental factors include heat and cold, the presence of water in the subbase or subgrade soil underlying the pavement, and frost heaves.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] High temperatures soften the asphalt binder, allowing heavy tire loads to deform the pavement into ruts.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Paradoxically, high heat and strong sunlight also cause the asphalt to oxidize, becoming stiffer and less resilient, leading to crack formation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Cold temperatures can cause cracks as the asphalt contracts.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Cold asphalt is also less resilient and more vulnerable to cracking.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Water trapped under the pavement softens the subbase and subgrade, making the road more vulnerable to traffic loads.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Water under the road freezes and expands in cold weather, causing and enlarging cracks.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In spring thaw, the ground thaws from the top down, so water is trapped between the pavement above and the still-frozen soil underneath.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This layer of saturated soil provides little support for the road above, leading to the formation of potholes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This is more of a problem for silty or clay soils than sandy or gravelly soils.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Some jurisdictions pass frost laws to reduce the allowable weight of trucks during the spring thaw season and protect their roads.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The damage a vehicle causes is roughly proportional to the axle load raised to the fourth power, so doubling the weight an axle carries actually causes 16 times as much damage.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Wheels cause the road to flex slightly, resulting in fatigue cracking, which often leads to crocodile cracking.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Slowly moving vehicles stress the road over a longer period of time, increasing ruts, cracking, and corrugations in the asphalt pavement.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Other causes of damage include heat damage from vehicle fires, or solvent action from chemical spills.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The life of a road can be prolonged through good design, construction and maintenance practices.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] During design, engineers measure the traffic on a road, paying special attention to the number and types of trucks.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] They also evaluate the subsoil to see how much load it can withstand.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The pavement and subbase thicknesses are designed to withstand the wheel loads.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Sometimes, geogrids are used to reinforce the subbase and further strengthen the roads.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Drainage, including ditches, storm drains and underdrains are used to remove water from the roadbed, preventing it from weakening the subbase and subsoil.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Sealcoating asphalt is a maintenance measure that helps keep water and petroleum products out of the pavement.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Maintaining and cleaning ditches and storm drains will extend the life of the road at low cost.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Sealing small cracks with bituminous crack sealer prevents water from enlarging cracks through frost weathering, or percolating down to the subbase and softening it.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] For somewhat more distressed roads, a chip seal or similar surface treatment may be applied.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] As the number, width and length of cracks increases, more intensive repairs are needed.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In order of generally increasing expense, these include thin asphalt overlays, multicourse overlays, grinding off the top course and overlaying, in-place recycling, or full-depth reconstruction of the roadway.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] It is far less expensive to keep a road in good condition than it is to repair it once it has deteriorated.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This is why some agencies place the priority on preventive maintenance of roads in good condition, rather than reconstructing roads in poor condition.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Poor roads are upgraded as resources and budget allow.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In terms of lifetime cost and long term pavement conditions, this will result in better system performance.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Agencies that concentrate on restoring their bad roads often find that by the time they have repaired them all, the roads that were in good condition have deteriorated.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Some agencies use a pavement management system to help prioritize maintenance and repairs.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Asphalt concrete is a recyclable material that can be reclaimed and reused both on-site and in asphalt plants.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The most common recycled component in asphalt concrete is reclaimed asphalt pavement (RAP).
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] RAP is recycled at a greater rate than any other material in the United States.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Many roofing shingles also contain asphalt, and asphalt concrete mixes may contain reclaimed asphalt shingles (RAS).
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Research has demonstrated that RAP and RAS can replace the need for up to 100% of the virgin aggregate and asphalt binder in a mix, but this percentage is typically lower due to regulatory requirements and performance concerns.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In 2019, new asphalt pavement mixtures produced in the United States contained, on average, 21.1% RAP and 0.2% RAS.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Recycled asphalt components may be reclaimed and transported to an asphalt plant for processing and use in new pavements, or the entire recycling process may be conducted in-place.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] While in-place recycling typically occurs on roadways and is specific to RAP, recycling in asphalt plants may utilize RAP, RAS, or both.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In 2019, an estimated 97.0 million tons of RAP and 1.1 million tons of RAS were accepted by asphalt plants in the United States.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] RAP is typically received by plants after being milled on-site, but pavements may also be ripped out in larger sections and crushed in the plant.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] RAP millings are typically stockpiled at plants before being incorporated into new asphalt mixes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Prior to mixing, stockpiled millings may be dried and any that have agglomerated in storage may have to be crushed.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] RAS may be received by asphalt plants as post-manufacturer waste directly from shingle factories, or they may be received as post-consumer waste at the end of their service life.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Processing of RAS includes grinding the shingles and sieving the grinds to remove oversized particles.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The grinds may also be screened with a magnetic sieve to remove nails and other metal debris.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The ground RAS is then dried, and the asphalt cement binder can be extracted.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] For further information on RAS processing, performance, and associated health and safety concerns, see Asphalt Shingles.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In-place recycling methods allow roadways to be rehabilitated by reclaiming the existing pavement, remixing, and repaving on-site.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In-place recycling techniques include rubblizing, hot in-place recycling, cold in-place recycling, and full-depth reclamation.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] For further information on in-place methods, see Road Surface.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] During its service life, the asphalt cement binder, which makes up about 5–6% of a typical asphalt concrete mix, naturally hardens and becomes stiffer.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This aging process primarily occurs due to oxidation, evaporation, exudation, and physical hardening.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] For this reason, asphalt mixes containing RAP and RAS are prone to exhibiting lower workability and increased susceptibility to fatigue cracking.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] These issues are avoidable if the recycled components are apportioned correctly in the mix.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Practicing proper storage and handling, such as by keeping RAP stockpiles out of damp areas or direct sunlight, is also important in avoiding quality issues.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The binder aging process may also produce some beneficial attributes, such as by contributing to higher levels of rutting resistance in asphalts containing RAP and RAS.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] One approach to balancing the performance aspects of RAP and RAS is to combine the recycled components with virgin aggregate and virgin asphalt binder.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] This approach can be effective when the recycled content in the mix is relatively low, and has a tendency to work more effectively with soft virgin binders.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] A 2020 study found that the addition of 5% RAS to a mix with a soft, low-grade virgin binder significantly increased the mix's rutting resistance while maintaining adequate fatigue cracking resistance.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In mixes with higher recycled content, the addition of virgin binder becomes less effective, and rejuvenators may be used.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Rejuvenators are additives that restore the physical and chemical properties of the aged binder.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] When conventional mixing methods are used in asphalt plants, the upper limit for RAP content before rejuvenators become necessary has been estimated at 50%.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Research has demonstrated that the use of rejuvenators at optimal doses can allow for mixes with 100% recycled components to meet the performance requirements of conventional asphalt concrete.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Beyond RAP and RAS, a range of waste materials can be re-used in place of virgin aggregate, or as rejuvenators.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Crumb rubber, generated from recycled tires, has been demonstrated to improve the fatigue resistance and flexural strength of asphalt mixes that contain RAP.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] In California, legislative mandates require the Department of Transportation to incorporate crumb rubber into asphalt paving materials.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Other recycled materials that are actively included in asphalt concrete mixes across the United States include steel slag, blast furnace slag, and cellulose fibers.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Further research has been conducted to discover new forms of waste that may be recycled into asphalt mixes.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] A 2020 study conducted in Melbourne, Australia presented a range of strategies for incorporating waste materials into asphalt concrete.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] The strategies presented in the study include the use of plastics, particularly high-density polyethylene, in asphalt binders, and the use of glass, brick, ceramic, and marble quarry waste in place of traditional aggregate.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Rejuvenators may also be produced from recycled materials, including waste engine oil, waste vegetable oil, and waste vegetable grease.
[src:industrial-metabolism/asphalt-concrete] Recently, discarded face masks have been incorporated into stone mastic.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] Recycled motor oil can be combusted as fuel, usually in plant boilers, space heaters, or industrial heating applications such as blast furnaces and cement kilns.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] When used motor oil is burned as fuel it must be burned at high temperatures to avoid gaseous pollution.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] Alternatively, waste motor oil can be distilled into diesel fuel or marine fuel in a process similar to oil re-refining, but without the final hydrotreating process.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] The lubrication properties of motor oil persist, even in used oil, and it can be recycled indefinitely.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] Used oil re-refining is the process of restoring used oil to new oil by removing chemical impurities, heavy metals and dirt.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] Used industrial and automotive oil is recycled at re-refineries.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] The used oil is first tested to determine suitability for re-refining, after which it is dehydrated and the water distillate is treated before being released into the environment.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] Dehydrating also removes the residual light fuel that can be used to power the refinery, and additionally captures ethylene glycol for re-use in recycled antifreeze.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] Next, industrial fuel is separated out of the used oil then vacuum distillation removes the lube cut (that is, the fraction suitable for reuse as lubricating oil) leaving a heavy oil that contains the used oil's additives and other by-products such as asphalt extender.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] The lube cut next undergoes hydro treating, or catalytic hydrogenation to remove residual polymers and other chemical compounds, and saturate carbon chains with hydrogen for greater stability.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] Final oil separation, or fractionating, separates the oil into three different oil grades: Light viscosity lubricants suitable for general lubricant applications, low viscosity lubricants for automotive and industrial applications, and high viscosity lubricants for heavy-duty applications.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] The oil that is produced in this step is referred to as re-refined base oil (RRBL).
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] The final step is blending additives into these three grades of oil products to produce final products with the right detergent and anti-friction qualities.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] Then each product is tested again for quality and purity before being released for sale to the public.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] The sludge ("residue") associated with engine oil recycling, which collects at the bottom of re-refining vacuum distillation towers, is known by various names, including "re-refined engine oil bottoms" (abbreviated "REOB" or "REOBs").
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] The oil in a car engine... contains a variety of additives to enhance the vehicle’s performance.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] These include polymers, viscosity modifiers, heat stabilizers, additional lubricants, and wear additives.
[src:industrial-metabolism/automotive-oil-recycling] Some producers of asphalt for paving have—openly or secretly—incorporated REOBs into their asphalt, creating some controversy and concern in the traffic engineering community, with some experts suggesting it reduces the durability of the resulting pavement.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] The term **autopoiesis** (from Greek αὐτo-*(auto)* 'self' and ποίησις*(poiesis)* 'creation, production'), one of several current theories of life, refers to a system capable of producing and maintaining itself by creating its own parts.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Chilean biologists Humberto Maturana and Francisco Varela, in the 1972 publication *Autopoiesis and Cognition: The Realization of the Living*, introduced the term to define the self-maintaining chemistry of living cells.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] The concept has since been applied to the fields of cognition, neurobiology, systems theory, architecture and sociology.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Niklas Luhmann briefly introduced the concept of autopoiesis to organizational theory.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] They describe the "space defined by an autopoietic system" as "self-contained", a space that "cannot be described by using dimensions that define another space.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Autopoiesis was originally presented as a system description that was said to define and explain the nature of living systems.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] A canonical example of an autopoietic system is the biological cell.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] The eukaryotic cell, for example, is made of various biochemical components such as nucleic acids and proteins, and is organized into bounded structures such as the cell nucleus, various organelles, a cell membrane and cytoskeleton.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] These structures, based on an internal flow of molecules and energy, *produce* the components which, in turn, continue to maintain the organized bounded structure that gives rise to these components.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] An autopoietic system is to be contrasted with an allopoietic system, such as a car factory, which uses raw materials (components) to generate a car (an organized structure) which is something *other* than itself (the factory).
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Autopoiesis in biological systems can be viewed as a network of constraints that work to maintain themselves.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] This concept has been called organizational closure or constraint closure and is closely related to the study of autocatalytic chemical networks where constraints are reactions required to sustain life.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Though others have often used the term as a synonym for self-organization, Maturana himself stated he would "[n]ever use the notion of self-organization ...
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] That is, if the organization of a thing changes, the thing changes".
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Moreover, an autopoietic system is autonomous and operationally closed, in the sense that there are sufficient processes within it to maintain the whole.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Autopoietic systems are "structurally coupled" with their medium, embedded in a dynamic of changes that can be recalled as sensory-motor coupling.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] This continuous dynamic is considered as a rudimentary form of knowledge or cognition and can be observed throughout life-forms.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] An application of the concept of autopoiesis to sociology can be found in Niklas Luhmann's Systems Theory, which was subsequently adapted by Bob Jessop in his studies of the capitalist state system.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Marjatta Maula adapted the concept of autopoiesis in a business context.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] The theory of autopoiesis has also been applied in the context of legal systems by not only Niklas Luhmann, but also Gunther Teubner.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] In the context of textual studies, Jerome McGann argues that texts are "autopoietic mechanisms operating as self-generating feedback systems that cannot be separated from those who manipulate and use them".
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Coding and markup appear allopoietic", McGann argues, but are generative parts of the system they serve to maintain, and thus language and print or electronic technology are autopoietic systems.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Recent work by Stankovski extends the concept of autopoiesis into the quantum domain, modelling it as a quantum-informational process grounded in physical interactions and addressing longstanding philosophical problems of identity, persistence, and knowledge within a unified formal framework.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Autopoiesis can be defined as the ratio between the complexity of a system and the complexity of its environment.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Autopoiesis has been proposed as a potential mechanism of abiogenesis, by which molecules evolved into more complex cells that could support the development of life.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Autopoiesis is just one of several current theories of life, including the chemoton of Tibor Gánti, the hypercycle of Manfred Eigen and Peter Schuster, the (*M,R*) systems of Robert Rosen, and the autocatalytic sets of Stuart Kauffman, similar to an earlier proposal by Freeman Dyson.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Nonetheless, there are more similarities than may be obvious at first sight, for example between Gánti and Rosen.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Until recently there have been almost no attempts to compare the different theories and discuss them together.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] An extensive discussion of the connection of autopoiesis to cognition is provided by Evan Thompson in his 2007 publication, *Mind in Life*.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] The basic notion of autopoiesis as involving constructive interaction with the environment is extended to include cognition.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Initially, Maturana defined cognition as behavior of an organism "with relevance to the maintenance of itself".
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] However, computer models that are self-maintaining but non-cognitive have been devised, so some additional restrictions are needed, and the suggestion is that the maintenance process, to be cognitive, involves readjustment of the internal workings of the system in some metabolic process.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] On this basis it is claimed that autopoiesis is a necessary but not a sufficient condition for cognition.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Thompson wrote that this distinction may or may not be fruitful, but what matters is that living systems involve autopoiesis and (if it is necessary to add this point) cognition as well.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] It can be noted that this definition of 'cognition' is restricted, and does not necessarily entail any awareness or consciousness by the living system.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] With the publication of The Embodied Mind in 1991, Varela, Thompson and Rosch applied autopoesis to make non-representationalist, and enactive models of mind, brain and behavior, which further developed embodied cognitive neuroscience, later culminating in neurophenomenology.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] The connection of autopoiesis to cognition, or if necessary, of living systems to cognition, is an objective assessment ascertainable by observation of a living system.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] One question that arises is about the connection between cognition seen in this manner and consciousness.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] The separation of cognition and consciousness recognizes that the organism may be unaware of the substratum where decisions are made.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] What is the connection between these realms?
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Thompson refers to this issue as the "explanatory gap", and one aspect of it is the hard problem of consciousness, how and why we have qualia.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] A second question is whether autopoiesis can provide a bridge between these concepts.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Thompson discusses this issue from the standpoint of enactivism.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] An autopoietic cell actively relates to its environment.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Its sensory responses trigger motor behavior governed by autopoiesis, and this behavior (it is claimed) is a simplified version of a nervous system behavior.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] The further claim is that real-time interactions like this require attention, and an implication of attention is awareness.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] There are multiple criticisms of the use of the term in both its original context, as an attempt to define and explain the living, and its various expanded usages, such as applying it to self-organizing systems in general or social systems in particular.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] An example is the assertion by Maturana and Varela that "We do not see what we do not see and what we do not see does not exist".
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] According to Razeto-Barry, the influence of *Autopoiesis and Cognition: The Realization of the Living* in mainstream biology has proven to be limited.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Razeto-Barry believes that autopoiesis is not commonly used as the criterion for life.
[src:industrial-metabolism/autopoiesis] Zoologist and philosopher Donna Haraway also criticizes the usage of the term, arguing that "nothing makes itself; nothing is really autopoietic or self-organizing", and suggests the use of *sympoiesis*, meaning "making-with", instead.
[src:industrial-metabolism/industrial-metabolism] Industrial metabolism presupposes a connection between different industrial activities by seeing them as part of a larger system, such as a material cycle or the supply chain of a commodity.
[src:industrial-metabolism/industrial-metabolism] Industrial metabolism is a subsystem of the anthropogenic or socioeconomic metabolism, which also comprises non-industrial human activities in households or the public sector.
